  "prompt": "What is the use of microbeads in cosmetics?",
  "response": "Microbeads are tiny plastic particles (typically less than 1mm in diameter) that were commonly used in cosmetic products like facial scrubs, body washes, and toothpaste as exfoliating agents. Their primary uses included:\n\n1. Exfoliation\n- Mechanically removing dead skin cells\n- Providing gentle scrubbing action\n- Creating smoother skin texture\n\n2. Skin cleansing\n- Helping to remove dirt and oil from pores\n- Providing additional cleansing action\n\n3. Enhancing product texture\n- Adding a smooth, polishing feel to cosmetic products\n- Creating visual appeal in personal care items\n\nHowever, microbeads have been widely banned in many countries due to significant environmental concerns:\n- They do not biodegrade\n- They pass through water treatment systems\n- They accumulate in oceans and waterways\n- They can be ingested by marine life\n- They potentially enter the food chain\n\nMany countries have passed legislation prohibiting the manufacture and sale of products containing microbeads, encouraging manufacturers to use natural alternatives like sugar, salt, or groundnut shells for exfoliation.\n\nAs a result, most modern cosmetic products now use biodegradable exfoliating ingredients instead of plastic microbeads.",
